# Hindi–English (Hinglish) Tokenizer

A from‑scratch bilingual tokenizer that converts mixed Hindi and English text into numerical tokens without using any prebuilt NLP tokenization libraries. The project demonstrates how large language models preprocess raw text before feeding it into neural networks.

## Overview

This project implements a custom Natural Language Processing (NLP) pipeline capable of handling:

* English words
* Hindi (Devanagari) words
* Hinglish mixed sentences
* Numbers and punctuation
* Unknown words using character fallback

The tokenizer dynamically builds its own vocabulary and converts sentences into numerical IDs and back to text.


## What is Tokenization?

Tokenization is the process of breaking raw text into smaller meaningful units called *tokens*. Machine learning models cannot understand text directly; they operate on numbers. Therefore, every word or subword must be mapped to a numerical representation.

Example:

Input:
मुझे assignment nahi mila
Tokenized Output:
[11, 8, 5, 12, 13, 14, 15]


## Features

* Custom vocabulary creation (no external tokenizer libraries)
* Unicode‑aware Hindi + English word detection
* Handles unseen words using character‑level fallback
* Bidirectional conversion (Encode & Decode)
* Modular architecture (separate components for clarity)


## Project Structure

hinglish_tokenizer/
│
├── main.py          # Entry point
├── normalizer.py    # Text cleaning
├── splitter.py      # Hindi + English word splitting
├── vocabulary.py    # Token ID management
└── tokenizer.py     # Pipeline integration


## Installation & Running

1. Clone or download the project
2. Open terminal in project folder
3. Run the program
python main.py


## How It Works

### 1. Normalization

* Converts text to lowercase
* Removes extra spaces

### 2. Splitting

Detects language using Unicode ranges:

* English letters (ASCII)
* Hindi letters (Devanagari Unicode \u0900–\u097F)
* Numbers
* Symbols

### 3. Vocabulary Building

Creates unique numeric ID for every token encountered during training.

### 4. Encoding

Converts tokens into numerical representation.

### 5. Unknown Word Handling

If a word does not exist in vocabulary, it is broken into characters and added dynamically.



## Example Run
Enter Sentence: मुझे assignment nahi mila

Encoded: [11, 8, 5, 12, 13, 14, 15]
Decoded: मुझे assignment nahi m i l a


## Learning Outcome

This project demonstrates the preprocessing stage used in modern Large Language Models (LLMs). It provides understanding of:

* Text normalization
* Multilingual tokenization
* Vocabulary mapping
* Open vocabulary handling
* NLP preprocessing pipelines

